

Japan's benchmark Nikkei stock index advanced for the sixth straight trading of gain Thursday to renew an almost five-year high as high-tech issues drew buying in tandem with their US counterparts' gains overnight.

The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 34.26 points, or 0.23 percent, from Tuesday to 14,742.58 for its highest closing since Dec. 14, 2000. The Japanese financial markets were closed Wednesday for a national holiday.

The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all First Section issues on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell 8.90 points, or 0.58 percent, to 1,517. 64, extending its losing streak to three trading days.

Advantest jumped 990 yen to 10,870 yen, ending above the 10,000 yen threshold for the first time in about three and a half years.

Major gainers were chemical, glass, textile, land transport and energy-related issues.

Retreating issues outnumbered advancing ones 1,116 to 469, with 76 shares ending unchanged.

Trading volume on the TSE's main section came to 2,322.16 million shares against Tuesday's 2,082.78 million shares.

Specialized nickel processor S-Science was the day's volume leader, down 7 yen to 67 yen.

Softbank was the most heavily traded issue by value. It gained 200 yen to 8,880 yen.

The TSE's Second Section index rose 18.97 points, or 0.42 percent, to 4,568.25 on a volume of 180.88 million shares. In Osaka, the near-term December Nikkei 225 index futures contract was up 10 points to 14,710.

